E=\dfrac{1}{2}\mu\mathbf{v}^2+U(r)
E=\dfrac{1}{2}\mu(\dot{r}^{2}+r^2\dot{\phi}^2)+U(r)?
 x = r \cos \phi 
 y = r \sin \phi 
 \dot{x} = \dot{r} \cos\phi - r \dot{\phi} \sin\phi 
 \dot{y} = \dot{r} \sin\phi + r \dot{\phi} \cos\phi 
 K = \frac{1}{2}\mu ( \dot{x}^2 + \dot{y}^2 ) 
   = \frac{1}{2}\mu ( \dot{r}^2 + r^2 \dot{\phi}^2 ) 
\mathbf{r}=r\mathbf{e}_r
\mathbf{v}=\frac{d\mathbf{r}}{dt}=\dot{\mathbf{v}}=\dot{r}\mathbf{e}_r+r\frac{d\mathbf{e}_r}{d\phi}\frac{d\phi}{dt}=\dot{r}\mathbf{e}_r+r\dot{\phi}\mathbf{e}_{\phi}
\mathbf{v}^2=v^2
v^2=\dot{r}^2+\left(r\dot{\phi}\right)^2
